TITLE: How Kyrsten Sinema's decision makes Democrats' 2024 Senate map tighter
SUMMARY: Arizona Sen. Kyrsten Sinema decided to shake up the political world on Friday by becoming an independent. The former Democrat is still caucusing with the party in the Senate, so the Democratic caucus still has 51 members. Now, instead of 49 Democrats and two independents within their ranks, the caucus has 48 Democrats and three independents.

SUMMARY: CNN's Sunlen Serfaty breaks down the GOP rebuttal by Sen. Katie Britt (R-AL) immediately following President Joe Biden's State of the Union address.
President Joe Biden released a new campaign ad addressing his age. CNN's Priscilla Alvarez is on the campaign trail with president.

While President Biden addressed the GOP-led failure of an immigration bill touted by his administration, Rep. Marjorie Taylor Greene (R-GA) interrupted him requesting he speak directly about Laken Riley, the Augusta University nursing student killed on the University of Georgia campus by a man who is not a US citizen.

To a viewer unhappy with Third Party efforts, CNN's Michael Smerconish responds that a pluraiity of the country labels itself as independents: "People are yearning for an alternative. So if the alternative is not to be in the year when we've got two wildly unpopular candidates, then let's stop even debating the concept of a third-party candidate because it'll never happen."

Responding to a viewer unhappy that he hadn't discussed Biden's State of the Union, CNN's Michael Smerconish says, "I thought that he turned in a very strong performance. TITLE: President Biden's 2024 State of the Union address
SUMMARY: President Joe Biden gave a forceful speech, with frequent ad-libs, highlighting his work on economic issues for the middle class in his State of the Union speech Thursday night.

With Americans unhappy about the Biden-Trump rematch, the No Labels group is moving forward to choose a "unity" ticket. Convention Chair Mike Rawlings calls attacks on the group "fearmongering" saying, "we want to break the mold."

CNN's Kim Brunhuber speaks with Kimberly Inez McGuire, the Executive Director of URGE, Unite for Reproductive & Gender Equity, about how reproductive rights are expected to influence the 2024 election in the U.S.

"Donald Trump tried to overthrow the federal government," says former House Chair Dick Gephardt, about potential third-party efforts. "That's the only thing to talk about in this election...We have to prevent someone coming to this office who will destroy the electoral process and this democracy."

"We're going to get run over by the Donald Trump train," says No Labels Convention Chair Mike Rawlings. "We didn't tie the Democrats to this track. We were the ones that saw this coming and said 'Get off the track.'"
